points.name: Nechung
points.description:
Nechung Monastery, Nechung Gompa, is the seat of the State Oracle of Tibet. It is also referred to as Sungi Gyelpoi Tsenkar, the "Demon Fortress of the Oracle King."
Wikipedia:Nechung

points.name: Sagrada Famlia
points.description:
The Baslica i Temple Expiatori de la Sagrada Famlia is a large unfinished Roman Catholic church in Barcelona, designed by Catalan architect Antoni Gaud (18521926).
Wikipedia:Sagrada Famlia
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Spain

points.name: Clear Air Force Station
points.description:
Clear Air Force Station ("Clear" colloq.) is an Alaska Air National Guard radar station for detecting incoming ICBMs and submarine-launched ballistic missiles to NORAD's Missile Correlation Center (MCC) and to provide Space Surveillance data to Air Force Space Command's Space Control Center (SCC).
Wikipedia:Clear Air Force Station
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:United States

points.name: Vottovaara Mountain
points.description:
The region was once covered by a huge ice sheet, several kilometers thick. About 10,000 years ago as the glacial ice retreated, it left behind a scraped and boulder strewn landscape with strange rocky features. One of the most striking feature at Vottovaara are its balancing stones, consisting of a large boulder propped up by smaller stones.
Wikipedia:Vottovaara Mountain
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Russia

points.name: Arunachala
points.description:
Arunachala refers to the holy hill at Tiruvannamalai in Tamil Nadu. The hill is also known by the names Arunagiri, Annamalai Hill, Arunachalam, Arunai, Sonagiri and Sonachalam. It is one of the five main shaivite holy places in South India.
Wikipedia:Arunachala
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:India

points.name: Uluru
points.description:
Uluru, also known as Ayers Rock is a large sandstone rock formation in the southern part of the Northern Territory in central Australia. It lies 335 km south west of the nearest large town, Alice Springs, 450 km by road. Uluru is sacred to the Pitjantjatjara Anangu, the Aboriginal people of the area. The area around the formation is home to an abundance of springs, waterholes, rock caves and ancient paintings.
Wikipedia:Uluru
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Australia

points.name: Samye
points.description:
The Samye Monastery or Samye Gompa is the first Buddhist monastery built in Tibet. It was probably first constructed between 775-9 CE under the patronage of King Trisong Detsen of Tibet who sought to revitalize Buddhism, which had declined since its introduction by King Songtsn Gampo in the 7th century. The monastery is in Dranang, Lhoka Prefecture. It was supposedly modeled on the design of Odantapuri in what is now Bihar, India.
Wikipedia:Samye
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Pyramid of Khui
points.description:
The pyramid of Khui is an ancient Egyptian funerary structure datable to the early First Intermediate Period (2181 BC - 2055 BC) and located in the royal necropolis of Dara, near Manfalut in Middle Egypt and close to the entrance of the Dakhla Oasis. It is generally attributed to Khui, an obscur ruler of the 8th Dynasty, perhaps reigning c. 2150 BC. The pyramid complex of Khui included a mortuary temple and a mud brick enclosure wall which, like the main pyramid, are now completely ruined.
Wikipedia:Pyramid of Khui
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Egypt

points.name: Sera Monastery
points.description:
Sera Monastery is one of the "great three" Gelug university monasteries of Tibet, located 2.01 km north of Lhasa and about 5 km north of the Jokhang. The other two are Ganden Monastery and Drepung Monastery. The origin of its name is attributed to a fact that the site where the monastery was built was surrounded by wild roses in bloom.
Wikipedia:Sera Monastery
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Shalu Monastery
points.description:
Shalu Monastery is small monastery 22 kilometres south of Shigatse in Tibet. Founded in 1040 by Chetsun Sherab Jungnay, for centuries it was renowned as a centre of scholarly learning and psychic training and its mural paintings were considered to be the most ancient and beautiful in Tibet. Shalu was the first of the major monasteries to be built by noble families of the Tsangpa during Tibet's great revival of Buddhism, and was an important center of the Sakya tradition.
Wikipedia:Shalu Monastery
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Jokhang
points.description:
The Jokhang is a Buddhist temple in Barkhor Square in Lhasa, the capital city of Tibet. Tibetans, in general, consider this temple as the most sacred and important temple in Tibet. The temple is currently maintained by the Gelug school, but they accept worshipers from all sects of Buddhism. The temple's architectural style is a mixture of Indian vihara design, Tibetan and Nepalese design.
Wikipedia:Jokhang
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Sakya Monastery
points.description:
Sakya Monastery, also known as Pel Sakya is a Buddhist monastery situated 25 km southeast of a bridge which is about 127 km west of Shigatse on the road to Tingri in Tibet.
Wikipedia:Sakya Monastery
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Drepung Monastery
points.description:
Drepung Monastery located at the foot of Mount Gephel, is one of the "great three" Gelukpa university monasteries of Tibet. The other two are Ganden and Sera. Drepung is the largest of all Tibetan monasteries and is located on the Gambo Utse mountain, five kilometers from the western suburb of Lhasa.
Wikipedia:Drepung Monastery
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Mount Sinai
points.description:
Mount Sinai, also known as Mount Horeb or Jebel Musa, is a mountain in the Sinai Peninsula of Egypt that is a possible location of the biblical Mount Sinai. The latter is mentioned many times in the Book of Exodus and other books of the Bible, and the Quran. According to Jewish, Christian, and Islamic tradition, the biblical Mount Sinai was the place where Moses received the Ten Commandments.
Wikipedia:Mount Sinai
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Egypt

points.name: Mount Everest
points.description:
Mount Everest, also known in Nepal as Sagarmth and in Tibet as Chomolungma, is Earth's highest mountain. It is located in the Mahalangur mountain range in Nepal and Tibet. Its peak is 8,848 metres (29,029 ft) above sea level. The international border between China (Tibet Autonomous Region) and Nepal runs across Everest's precise summit point.
Wikipedia:Mount Everest
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Mount Taranaki
points.description:
Mount Taranaki, or Mount Egmont, is an active but quiescent stratovolcano in the Taranaki region on the west coast of New Zealand's North Island. Although the mountain is more commonly referred to as Taranaki, it has two official names under the alternative names policy of the New Zealand Geographic Board. The 2518-metre-high mountain is one of the most symmetrical volcanic cones in the world. There is a secondary cone, Fanthams Peak, 1,966 metres (6,450 ft), on the south side.
Wikipedia:Mount Taranaki
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:New Zealand

points.name: Nam Co
points.description:
Namtso or Lake Nam (officially: Nam Co is a mountain lake on the border between Damxung County of Lhasa prefecture-level city and Baingoin County of Nagqu Prefecture in the Tibet Autonomous Region of China, approximately 112 kilometres (70 mi) NNW of Lhasa.
Wikipedia:Nam Co
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Siecha Lakes
points.description:
The Siecha Lakes are three glacial lakes located in the Chingaza Natural National Park in Cundinamarca, Colombia. The Andean lakes are considered sacred in the religion of the Muisca people who inhabited the area before the Spanish conquest in the 1530s.
Wikipedia:Siecha Lakes
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Colombia

points.name: Saksaywaman
points.description:
Saksaywaman is a citadel on the northern outskirts of the city of Cusco, Peru, the historic capital of the Inca Empire. Sections were first built by the Killke culture about 1100; they had occupied the area since 900. The complex was expanded and added to by the Inca from the 13th century; they built dry stone walls constructed of huge stones. The workers carefully cut the boulders to fit them together tightly without mortar. The site is at an altitude of 3,701 m (12,142 ft).
Wikipedia:Saksaywaman
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Peru

points.name: Ur
points.description:
Ur was an important Sumerian city-state in ancient Mesopotamia, located at the site of modern Tell el-Muqayyar in south Iraq's Dhi Qar Governorate. Although Ur was once a coastal city near the mouth of the Euphrates on the Persian Gulf, the coastline has shifted and the city is now well inland, south of the Euphrates on its right bank, 16 kilometres (9.9 mi) from Nasiriyah.
Wikipedia:Ur
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Iraq

points.name: Erdmannlistein
points.description:
Erdmannlistein
Wikipedia:Erdmannlistein

Country:Switzerland

points.name: Mount Damavand
points.description:
Mount Damavand is a dormant stratovolcano and is the highest peak in Iran and Western Asia, the highest volcano in Asia, and the 3rd highest volcano in the Eastern Hemisphere (after Mount Kilimanjaro and Mount Elbrus), at an elevation of 5,609 metres. Damvand has a special place in Persian mythology and folklore.
Wikipedia:Mount Damavand
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Iran

points.name: Gornaya Shoria megaliths
points.description:
The Gornaya Shoria megaliths (Mount Shoria megaliths) are rock formations that are part of Gornaya Shoria (Russian: ) in southern Siberia, Russia, lying to the east of the Altay Mountains. Popular, often fringe, articles have claimed these rock formations to be gigantic prehistoric man-made blocks, or megaliths. It is reported that the largest pieces or blocks of stone have estimated weights between three and four thousand tons, which would make them larger than the megaliths at Baalbek, in Lebanon.
Wikipedia:Gornaya Shoria megaliths
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Russia

points.name: Ganden Monastery
points.description:
Ganden Monastery or Ganden Namgyeling is one of the "great three" Gelug university monasteries of Tibet, China. Ganden Monastery was founded in 1409 by Je Tsongkhapa Lozang-dragpa, founder of the Gelug order. The monastery was destroyed after 1959, but has since been partially rebuilt.
Wikipedia:Ganden Monastery
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Lake Iguaque
points.description:
Lake Iguaque is a lake located in the Boyac Department of Colombia. The lake and the surrounding area was declared a Flora and Fauna Sanctuary in 1977.
Wikipedia:Lake Iguaque
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Colombia

points.name: Volcn de Colima
points.description:
The Volcn de Colima, also known as Volcn de Fuego, is part of the Colima Volcanic Complex (CVC) consisting of Volcn de Colima, Nevado de Colima and the eroded El Cantaro (listed as extinct). It is the youngest of the three and as of 2015 is one of the most active volcanos in Mexico and in North America. It has erupted more than 40 times since 1576. One of the largest eruptions was on January 2024, 1913. Nevado de Colima, also known as Tzapotpetl, lies 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) north of its more active neighbor and is the taller of the two at 4,271+ meters (14,015+ ft). It is the 26th-most prominent peak in North America.
Wikipedia:Volcn de Colima
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Mexico

points.name: Yamdrok Lake
points.description:
Yamdrok Lake (also known as Yamdrok Yumtso or Yamzho Yumco) is a freshwater lake in Tibet, it is one of the three largest sacred lakes in Tibet. It is over 72 km (45 mi) long. The lake is surrounded by many snow-capped mountains and is fed by numerous small streams. The lake has an outlet stream at its far western end. Around 90 km to the west of the lake lies the Tibetan town of Gyantse and Lhasa is a hundred km to the northeast. According to local mythology, Yamdok Yumtso lake is the transformation of a goddess.
Wikipedia:Yamdrok Lake
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Denisova Cave
points.description:
Denisova Cave is a cave in the Bashelaksky Range of the Altai mountains, Siberia, Russia. The cave is of great paleoarchaeological and paleontological interest. Bone fragments of the Denisova hominin, sometimes called the "X woman" (referring to the maternal descent of mitochondrial DNA) originate from the cave, including artifacts dated to ~40,000 BP. The cave is located in a region thought to have been inhabited concurrently in the past by Neanderthals and modern humans.
Wikipedia:Denisova Cave
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Links:http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2015/09/siberian-cave-was-home-generations-mysterious-ancient-humans
Country:Russia

points.name: Blue Mountains (New South Wales)
points.description:
The Blue Mountains is a mountainous region and a mountain range located in New South Wales, Australia. There have been some very unusual happenings on the Blue Mountains over recent years which have yet to be given a proper explanation by the authorities concerned, yet is is likely that no explanation no matter how guarded can be offered without it becoming obvious to most people that we are not alone in this universe. The unusual happenings of which I speak are the 600 or so reports of unidentified flying objects that have been seen over, or on the Blue Mountains west of Sydney in the last few years. The Jamieson Valley and its surrounding environs have been the scene of many spectacular UFO events.
Wikipedia:Blue Mountains (New South Wales)
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Links:http://www.mysteriousaustralia.com/strangephenomenonl.html
Country:Australia

points.name: Potala Palace
points.description:
The Potala Palace in Lhasa, Tibet Autonomous Region was the chief residence of the Dalai Lama until the 14th Dalai Lama fled to India during the 1959 Tibetan uprising. It is now a museum and World Heritage Site. The palace is named after Mount Potalaka, the mythical abode of the bodhisattva Avalokitevara. The 5th Dalai Lama started its construction in 1645 after one of his spiritual advisers, Konchog Chophel (died 1646), pointed out that the site was ideal as a seat of government, situated as it is between Drepung and Sera monasteries and the old city of Lhasa. It may overlay the remains of an earlier fortress called the White or Red Palace on the site, built by Songtsn Gampo in 637.
Wikipedia:Potala Palace
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:China

points.name: Dancing Wood
points.description:
Phenomenon of Dancing wood. This is indeed a unique place in Kaliningrad region, Russia, in the national park Curonian, it is called Dancing woods. To understand the phenomenon of twisted trees anomaly, many scientists have tried different hypothesis: environmental factors, genetic factors, exposure to viruses or pests, and even a special cosmic energy of the place. The place is far from being normal, if you come in to a few meters, you feel something is wrong, as if its the world of spirits, the place has a strong energy. The staff of the national park do not believe in supernatural, they see the answer in the geomagnetic field. A similar place called Troll Forest is in Denmark, and it is also on the Baltic coast. No one has fully explained the nature of this phenomenon.
Wikipedia:Dancing Wood
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Links:http://viola.bz/phenomenon-of-dancing-wood/
Country:Russia

points.name: Ratanab
points.description:
The founders of this gigantic lost city (Dakila project, Brazil) consider it to be the ancient capital of the world. According to them, all the underground tunnels around the world seem to be connected to it. Filled with treasures and constructions, they say it was built by some race of humanoids called Murils, who were here on Earth way before Atlantians and Lemurians. They consider it now to be the oldest (millions of years old) ancient civilization on Earth.
Wikipedia:Ratanab
Custodian:Yasser Rabello (The Alchemist)
Country:Brazil

points.name: Obelisk of So Paulo
points.description:
Obelisk of So Paulo or Obelisk of Ibirapuera is an obelisk in Ibirapuera Park in the city of So Paulo, Brazil. This monument is a symbol of the Constitutionalist Revolution of 1932, and the biggest monument of the city of So Paulo. The height of the monument is 72 meters. The construction of the monument was started in 1947 and completed in 1970.
Wikipedia:Obelisk of So Paulo
Custodian:www.leylines.net
Country:Brazil
